<caption httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30925" pageId="435" pageNumber="436" start="Figure 24" startId="F24">
<paragraph pageId="435" pageNumber="436">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="435" pageNumber="436">Figure 24.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1823" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Mioptachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="435" pageNumber="436" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicauda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="435" pageNumber="436">Mioptachys flavicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Say). This small species is a characteristic element of the fauna that lives under the bark of dead deciduous trees. Despite its size, it is easily recognized in the field by its conspicuous yellow apical third of the elytra. Thomas Say, the first entomologist born on this continent worthy of the name, was struck by the coloration and for that reason proposed the name 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="435" pageNumber="436">flavicauda</emphasis>
, derived from the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="435" pageNumber="436">flavus</emphasis>
(yellow) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="435" pageNumber="436">cauda</emphasis>
(tail), for the species.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
